Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Minutes:  Clerk/T. Lehman.  Special Pros K R Wells appeared for the State.  Deft appeared in person w/Atty Carmen Lassiter.  Report has been received from Dr. Luzi.  Dr. Luzi's report states the deft is not competent at this time to proceed and is not likely to become competent within one year.  All parties concur with the findings in the report.  Defense counsel also reports the deft is presently under a guardianship/protective placement supervision.  Court finds the deft is not competent to proceed and will not likely become competent within one year.  The proceedings are suspended at this time and the court refers this matter to the Corp Counsel.  Court requests the DA's office notify Corp Counsel.  Bond to continue at this time.
